    <div xml:id="PN307">
      <lg type="edition">
<l>ācā kentai yāṇṭuḷaṉ kollō</l>
<l>kuṉṟat taṉṉa kaḷiṟṟoṭu paṭṭōṉ</l>
<l>vampalaṉ pōla tōṉṟu mutukkāṇ</l>
<l>vēṉal variyaṇil vālat taṉṉa</l>
<l>kāṉa vūkiṟ kaḻaṉṟuku mutuvī</l>
<l>yariyal vāṉkuḻaṟ curiya ṟaṅka</l>
<l>nīrum pullu mīyā tumaṇar</l>
<l>yārumil loruciṟai muṭattoṭu tuṟanta</l>
<l>vāḻā vālpaka ṭēyppa teṟuvar</l>
<l>pēruyir koḷḷu mātō vatukkaṇṭu</l>
<l>vēciṉa yāṉai vēntaṉu mikkaḷat</l>
<l>teñcaliṉ ciṟantatu piṟitoṉ ṟilleṉa</l>
<l>paṇkoḷaṟ karumai nōkki</l>
<l>neñcaṟa vīḻnta puraimai yōṉē.</l>
</lg>
<lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>[Our] father who is [our] support, where is he? (1)</l>
<l>He who fell with an elephant bull like a hill, (2)</l>
<l>he appears like a stranger. Look there. (3)</l>
<l>While in the curls of [his] white locks stay bunches(?) (6) </l>
<l>of old blossoms shed after having become lose from the forest Ūku tree, (5)</l>
<l>like the tail of a striped squirrel in summer, (4)</l>
<l>resembling a white bull that is [barely] alive, (9a-c)</l>
<l>abandoned with lameness on one side where there is no one (8)</l>
<l>by the salt-merchants who give neither water nor grass, (7)</l>
<l>would he not take the great lives of the opponents, (9d-10c)</l>
<l>the great man who fell, seeing that (10d+14cd)</l>
<l>[and] looking at the difficulty of gaining a tune [for oneself], thinking (13)</l>
<l>“since also the king with the elephant in hot anger stayed behind (12)</l>
<l>on this field, there is nothing else that is excellent,” (11)</l>
<l>so that [my heart] heart stops? (14ab)</l>
</lg>
